# React components

## Component shape

Use **arrow functions** for all components (pages, widgets, features, shared UI, providers).

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
interface ButtonProps extends ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement> {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'ghost'
}

export const Button = ({
  variant = 'primary',
  className,
  ...props
}: ButtonProps): React.JSX.Element => {
  return <button className={cn(variants[variant], className)} {...props} />
}

// ❌ BAD
function Button({ variant = 'primary' }: ButtonProps): React.JSX.Element {
  return <button />
}
```

## Exports

- Prefer **named exports** (`export const Foo`).
- Avoid `export default` in new code.
- File name = component name (`Button.tsx` → `Button`).

## Props

- Props interface: `ComponentNameProps`, declared above the component.
- Return type: `React.JSX.Element` (or `React.JSX.Element | null` when needed).

## Sub-components

Private helpers in the same file — arrow functions, not exported:

```tsx
const CategoryPill = ({ option }: { option: CategoryOption }): React.JSX.Element => (...)
```

## Hooks & providers

Same arrow style:

```tsx
export const useAuth = (): AuthContextValue => { ... }
export const AuthProvider = ({ children }: { children: ReactNode }): React.JSX.Element => { ... }
```

## Exceptions

- `forwardRef`: wrap arrow component in `forwardRef`, export with named export.
- Generic components with constrained type params: arrow is fine; unconstrained generics may need a function declaration (rare).

## Layer placement (FSD)

| Layer | Path | Example |
|-------|------|---------|
| pages | `pages/` | route screens |
| widgets | `widgets/` | dashboard blocks |
| features | `features/*/ui/` | forms, toggles |
| shared UI | `shared/ui/` | Form, Modal, ChartCard |
| legacy | `components/` | migrate to `shared/ui` over time |

Logic stays in `model/` hooks; components stay presentational where possible.
